Reflection Essay
	Have you ever adjusted your identity just to fit the norm? Most people at some point in their life have changed something about themselves in order to fit in. We grow up and think that we must fit our specific gender stereotypes. As a girl you are expected to wear pink, play with dolls, wear dresses, and have long hair. If you want to play a sport and you’re a girl, its suggested that you either dance or cheerlead. We shouldn’t be conditioned at such a young age that certain styles, colors, interests, or athletics fall into gender categories.
	Up until high school, I was what was known as a “tomboy”. I grew up on a farm, so I enjoyed activities such as hunting, fishing, and riding four-wheelers. Part of these hobbies came from being part of a family of all boys. All of my cousins were boys, and I also had a younger brother. We would play different sports like basketball, football, and baseball. I was always just hanging out with my family and never understood these activities weren’t typically participated in by girls. 
	Not only did I act the part of a tomboy, I also dressed like it. I was always wearing baggy t-shirts and athletic shorts. Dresses, skirts, and sandals were not part of my wardrobe. Additionally, I wouldn’t wear colors such as pink or purple. All of my clothes were either blue, black, or grey. Many of my mom’s friends or my family members would always tell her to dress me in pink so I would look more like a girl. However, my mom didn’t like pink or bright colors anyways, so I never had to worry about that.
	When I got to high school, I was districted to a school in the city. I decided that I needed to switch up my look so I would fit in. I changed out my typical tomboy look for skirts and crop tops. I even dyed my hair blonde and started growing it out. It worked and I made friends quickly, but it didn’t really feel like me. I wanted to get involved with something that actually felt true to my interests, so I tried out and made the women’s basketball team at my high school. It was the best decision I made but I was quickly brought back down again. All of the guys on the men’s team would tell us that women’s basketball isn’t a real sport. I was the team captain so I tried to help the other girls get past these comments, however I couldn’t really get over them myself. I started to question if they were right. Additionally, some of the guys in my grade would tell me that I was “too pretty to play basketball,” and that I should do something that was “more girly” such as cheerleading. Even though I loved playing basketball, I ended up quitting my junior year because I was tired of all the remarks about my looks and ability to play a sport as a girl.
	Candace West and Don Zimmerman wrote an article titled, “Doing Gender.” It talks about how gender is an ongoing accomplishment in your everyday interactions. Your sex is your biological differences that you were born with. However, your gender is the societal expectation of you based on your sex. Therefore, doing gender is behaving as expected based on your biological identifiers.
	Naomi Wolf wrote about the “Beauty Myth.” The beauty myth is essentially an idea that is designed to control women by telling them that their identity is in their beauty. This makes women become more obsessed with how they look than pursuing a strong leadership role. This makes it hard for women to come together and make a community since they aren’t striving for power together. It is a tactic used by men and political authorities to keep women virtually submissive. They want women to believe that a woman is more desirable if she is domesticated and beautiful.
	When I was growing up, I wasn’t “doing gender” to societies standards. Society has set standards for girls and boys. Girls are told in order to be a real girl you need to have long hair, wear dresses, paint your fingernails, wear makeup. They are also told to be emotional and subservient. As a boy you are told to have short hair, wear suits, and not to wear makeup. They are told to be stoic and dominate. If you don’t follow these expectations, then you are told you aren’t a real girl or boy. As a child I was typically taking part in activities and wearing clothes that were typically reserved for boys. This is why I was always called a tomboy. However, I never wasn’t a real girl. These were activities that I truly enjoyed. We shouldn’t grow up and be told by society that we can’t dress a certain way or do certain activities because of our sex. We shouldn’t have to prove that we are a real girl or boy by doing gender. These expectations keep people from being their true authentic self.
	When I was in high school, I played directly into the beauty myth. I became obsessed with how others viewed me. I wanted everyone to like me so bad that I changed myself to the point where I didn’t recognize myself anymore. I changed my hair color because I thought it would make me more desirable. Additionally, when my ability to play basketball was doubted, I didn’t try to stand up for myself. I would just brush it off when I could have done more about it. Even when I was told I shouldn’t play basketball because I didn’t look the part, I didn’t even try to disagree. It all led me to quitting. This is exactly what Wolf meant when she talks about how women won’t be able to form a community because they become more obsessed with their beauty than their fight for power.
	Society tries to control women in multiple ways. They try to question their beauty so that they won’t try to fight for more power. They also try to convince women that they aren’t a true woman if they participate in activities or dress different than the norm. This became apparent to me throughout my whole life. The beauty myth along with doing gender have forced me multiple times to adjust my identity in order to fit societies standards. We need to change societies expectations that a woman’s identity is in her beauty to hinder her drive for power. We also need to teach the younger generations that they can participate in any sport, activity, and dress however they want. Just because a girl doesn’t want to wear skirts and dresses doesn’t make them any less of a real girl. We also need to teach society as a whole not to judge others based on their appearance. The number of times I was told I should dress differently eventually did drive me to changing my appearance. We shouldn’t be convinced to change our appearance to fit societies standards. I am a real woman no matter what activities I choose to participate in and how I decide to dress.

Alienation in the Workplace and how it Affects a Worker.
Have you ever been unsatisfied with your work? Feel as though your job doesn’t stimulate your creativity? Does your job give you a sense of purpose? These feelings are not uncommon with in the workplace, and many people around the world experience alienation within their place of work. Karl Marx, a German sociologist, explained these feelings and the concept of alienation in “Estranged Labor”. 
Karl Marx believed that the feeling of alienation comes from a person labor. He describes four different types of alienation and why this alienation is experienced by the worker. What Karl Marx does not explain however is how this alienation effects the worker outside of their workplace. How it affects their social life and their mental wellbeing. After further research into this matter, it is clear that alienation within the workplace has a distinct negative effect on a person life outside of the workplace. 
The four different types of alienation that Karl Marx describes are the separation the worker has to the product, the estrangement that the worker feels during the production process, alienation from the human identity, and finally alienation of man to man. These feelings of alienation all stem from different things but they all occur within the workplace, and they all have a negative effect on the worker. A study titled “The effects of work alienation on organizational commitment, work effort, and work-to-family enrichment” focused on the powerlessness and the meaninglessness aspect of alienation. Karl Marx's concept and theory of alienation is predominantly in regard to the worker, and it focuses on how the capitalist production process is what makes the worker feel alienated. Marx believed that alienation is the result of being within a society where there are social classes, and that wage labor resulted in a feeling of alienation. Marx also believed that our society was divided into two classes, the first one being capitalist, and the second one being the laborer’s. He argued that labor is an essential part to a man's core concept of himself. When a worker creates something, he puts himself into that object, but alienation occurs because the production of that object is not his. As the worker creates more this feeling of alienation grows. In our economy work is about surviving, and we do not work for the sake of ourselves. For the labor, their work is not driven from the core concept of themselves but instead driven by survival. The alienation that occurs when a worker feels alienated from the human identity, or as Marx called it "species being”, occurs when the labor feels separated from their basic humanity. Referring to the idea that labor is the essential part of a man's core identity, Marx believed that we are what we create. Due to capitalism, private ownership, and the division of labor however a worker has no ownership over his creations. This division between the capitalist and the labor creates another form of alienation between man and man. Due to the labor producing goods for others it separates the worker from the person who truly "owns" the goods being produced. Therefore, creating a divide between man and their fellow man.
The purpose of this study was to analyze the effects of work elimination on organizational commitment, work effort, and work to family enrichment. They had three hypotheses that they studied the first one is that work alienation will be negatively related to passive performance at work, the second one is that work alienation will be negatively related to active performance at work, and the third and final one is that work alienation will be negatively related to life outside of work. The way that they test their hypotheses was by using surveys collected among a national sample of midwives in the Netherlands. They chose to do midwives because of their growing scarcity as well as the fact that most midwives are the primary caregivers within their families. This study in particular is important because it recognizes that work and family are no longer separate life demands but that they are becoming increasingly related, therefore also recognizing that work has an effect on life at home. The three things that the study was looking at is organizational commitment, work effort, and work to family enrichment. Organizational commitment is the emotional feeling that an employee has towards the organization that they are employed to, workers who experienced this are more likely to stay with the organization because they are able to identify with it.  This is also an important feeling for the worker to experience because it positively influences the employees’ health and their well-being. Work effort is when employee extends their work beyond what is written in their employment contract. Feelings of powerlessness or meaninglessness can affect the performance of a workers work effort.  The two aspects of alienation, powerlessness, and meaninglessness are negatively related to organizational commitment and work effort. This is due to the fact that having control over the way that work is done is likely to increase organizational commitment and work effort within the worker. Available studies show that there is a negative relationship between meaninglessness and job performance. A lot of them also show that meaninglessness is negatively related to a worker’s commitment to their work. Meaninglessness and job satisfaction as well as work effort also have a negative relationship. The study found that work powerlessness and meaninglessness both have a significant negative influence on organizational commitment of workers. This means that when workers feel that their work has no meaning and when they have no power over their work, they are less committed to their job or their employer. The data of the study also shows that when the worker feels that they have no meaning in their work or when they feel powerless at work, they are less willing to put effort into their jobs. Finally, the study showed that work meaninglessness does in fact have a negative effect on work family relationships, it found that when the worker felt that their work was not important, they also experienced less positivity in their family life.
Another study titled "on the personal consequences of alienation in work" aimed to study the consequences of feeling alienated at work. They conducted the study by examining a random sample that consisted of working males in a Swedish community. The consequences that are usually allotted to work alienation consist of hostility, political withdraw, a sense of powerlessness, and the seeking of a status. Alienation can be considered the wrongful denial of a man to his potential. This concept connects to mark's idea that a man's labor is his core concept of self. When a man is consistently working in an environment or a job that is unfulfilling it can have very serious social affects. The consequences of unfulfilling labor do not just consist of the refusal of a personal fulfilment but also consists of trouble within a person's political life, as well as their social life and many other aspects outside of the workplace. Alienation within the workplace not only affects a worker at their job but also at social events, political affairs, and their home life as well. The theory is that the effect of alienation in the workplace trickles into a person's social and personal life therefore affecting those aspects as well. The feeling of powerlessness also has a negative effect on the worker's mental well-being. This study in particular raises questions about what can alleviate the feeling of alienation. Things such as becoming a member the worker's occupation, friendships with fellow workers, especially those who work face to face. The friendship idea in particular has been found to help alleviate the feelings of being alienated within the workplace. This study in particular found that there was little evidence that length alienated work to being less engaged in political and social matters. However, the study also raised interesting questions about what factors could have played a role in these findings. Like whether or not outside friendships contributed to the worker's well-being. 
While looking further into Karl Marx’s theory of alienation I realized that it is still a very prevalent issue to this day, and that lots of people are studying the effect that it has on workers who experience it. Marx contributed a worker’s creations or their work to their sense of purpose, explaining that a man’s core concept of self was what he creates. Feeling as though one has no control or ownership over their creations and their work leads to alienation. This occurs because of the separation between the two classes the laborer, and the capitalist. The laborer has no ownership over what they create therefore creating a divided between the worker and their work. As human beings we find purpose in our work, and we work for our own self-fulfillment, but in today’s society most people have to work for survival. Working only because you have to in order to survive does not give a sense of fulfillment and leads to the separation between the worker and their job. Feelings of alienation contribute and led to feelings powerlessness and meaninglessness within and outside of a person’s job. Even though the studies had different results in regards to how alienation affects the worker outside of the workforce, they both found that it did have some type of affect. The first study found that those who felt a feeling of meaninglessness within their jobs, also felt less positivity within their home life. That there was a direct negative correlation between feelings of alienation to negative feelings outside of work. Feelings of alienation also affect the workers work effort, when they feel as though their job has no meaning, they are less willing to put effort into their jobs. Alienation not only effects a person while at work but also outside of their job, such as in their home life and their social lives. The second study found that friendships within the workplace can help to lessen or alleviate feelings of alienation, especially when the friends are those who work closely with you. In conclusion alienation within the workplace has a negative effect on personal aspects of a worker’s life, such as their family and social lives.

Ever since I was young I have had something of an identity crisis. My mother is a second generation American, but she grew up learning Spanish as her first language and visited Mexico often. My father grew up in Mexico as well and moved to America when he married my mother. I was born in Ohio and learned Spanish as my first language, but around the time I got to middle school I never knew whether to call myself an American or a Mexican - in my head both of my parents were Mexicans, so it made sense for me to be Mexican. At the same time I grew up in American culture, spoke English and had forgotten most of my Spanish, and though I knew more about Mexican culture than the average American it did not feel like my own culture. This caused me to not know who I was internally, which made me close myself off. As I grew older though I started to look laterally and came to realize more that who I am is not something that can be easily attributed to any one label. 
	When I look back to my hometown of Medina, Ohio there are many things that I’m reminded about. It was a nice little town and I still get nostalgic thinking back to the little downtown area that I and my class went to for a field trip and my mom picked me up from, or thinking about the time we showed our cousins around our picturesque house, complete with a big field, a farmhouse, woods, and our neighbors even had a pond. I paint this picture to show that my memories of my hometown are significant mainly due to imagery and family. It is not as though I lacked interaction outside of that - I went to preschool, Sunday school, I interacted with other children my age, but I don’t remember it - despite all that I remember my family mostly. This is due to the disconnect I felt with my peers, as I had lost a sense of myself.
	In sociology there are a few concepts of the self that can be used to explain this situation, with the first of these being “The Self and its Selves,” from William James. James explains that each self is made up of four different constituents, those being the material, social, spiritual selves and then the pure ego. The material self is how we tie our physical traits and possessions into our character - we take pride in how we look, how we dress and the conditions we keep things because that is a reflection of us. The social self is how we want to be perceived in different social situations by our peers, and there are as many social selves as there are interactions that we have with others. The spiritual self is the self that we can see through introspection, and informs the first two, while the pure ego is the “soul” of a person, cannot really be seen, but informs completely the spiritual self. Though this can be used to explain my situation, there are two facets of the self that get left out, as the two integral selves for my childhood are social self and spiritual self.
	I grew up with my family - which sounds obvious, but contrasts with the fact that I did not grow up with my peers. When I was with my family I did not need to explain my social self as it was evident through all the years we had spent together. They knew how to pronounce my name, my nickname, what I liked and did not like, etc. When I was with new peers not only did I need to build a new relationship but there was already a need to explain - how to pronounce my name, my nickname, why it was the way it was, etc. It is an odd thing to have shaped me the way it has, but my full name (and even nickname) marked me as “different” from the beginning. It is not everyday that you meet a “Cuauhtemoc,” (let alone a “Temo”) and people always had questions on how to pronounce both of these since I was young. This did not bother me when I was very young - kids asked questions to each other all the time. As this continued into elementary school though I started to question myself - why is it that every stranger was so interested in this name of mine? It was a very exotic name obviously, but then this got me to examine my spiritual self, which I had no need to do before as I was surrounded by family. This introspection led to a realization - I can not speak Spanish anymore, and had not been able to for quite some time.
	When I realized that I, a Mexican kid, could not speak Spanish, it caused much cognitive dissonance in my head and I started questioning myself. “What good is being a Mexican if I can’t even speak Spanish? Doesn’t that mean I’m not anything - not American because of my parents, but not Mexican either?” I asked this and many other questions in my head constantly, and the answer I came to was that I was no longer Mexican - I had thrown it away whether I liked it or not, and that is my punishment for doing so. Very melodramatic, but it was a truly fundamental shift to how I perceived myself. I continued to not need to explain myself to my siblings as our dynamic did not change, but the way I saw myself changed, which goes into the second sociological concept of self: the looking glass self.
	James Cooley is the mind behind the looking glass self and the best way to describe it is “perceived perception.” Cooley states that everyone acts the way that they think others perceive them. So if I as a student believe that a teacher thinks I am a disruptive student, I am more likely to act like a disruptive student. It is a self fulfilling prophecy of sorts that is also built off of the perception of others that we have. To go back to the example, not only do I think that the teacher has a preconceived notion about me, but that notion is based on how I perceive that teacher as well - maybe I make a few jokes in class and the teacher always tells me to stop disrupting. I then think the teacher is a stick in the mud, which informs how I imagine the teacher's perception. This concept of the looking glass self came into play during this time when I started thinking about who I was, but it does explain the situation on its own.
	Because growing up so many people had questions and I was already having doubts about myself I inadvertently started using the looking glass self, which started to inform my behavior. I saw myself as an outsider or outcast to my peers; my name obviously marked me as different yet at the same time I had fair skin and looked Caucasian, and I had no command of the Spanish language. Too light for the Hispanics, too exotic for the Caucasians I thought. And I continued to think that for a long time, until around my high school years when I learned to do nothing differently except the one thing that got me into that position - think.
	As I slowly got friends and started to look around to my peers, I started to notice that labels told you about as many letters as they were. My older brother could be considered a jock, but he graduated with above a 4.0 gpa and liked to sing. My best friend in middle school was a “geek,” but the only geeky thing about him was that he liked computers and computer games - other than that he was not much of a geek. This caused a change in how I decided to perceive people, not by their social self but by their internal self. The pure ego as mentioned before for lack of a better term is the soul of someone. And though it informs every other part of yourself, it is not something that can be probed or introspected on - all we can see are the effects, that being the other facets of self. As I got older I started to see my peers not based off of their material or social selves, but instead their internal self. George Mead developed a concept of self that is very similar to James’, that being the “I and Me.”
	The I and Me is a simple concept - the “I” is the internal self ( like the spiritual self and pure ego), whereas the “me” is the social self (material and social selves). The “I” reacts to stimuli, and the “me” filters these through what it has learned of social situations. This concept more holistically explain my younger self - there was a change in how my “I” was viewed, and that lead to a loss in what the “me” should do, causing me to close myself off. As I grew older though I realized that each individual's social selves tend to be unique to them, and that a label of any kind rarely does anyone “self” justice. So how did I start to view myself? Although I was American and Hispanic, above both of those things I was me. Not entirely in the Mead sense - I simply put my labels beneath my social and internal self. I wrongly believed that race or ethnicity informed more of my internal self than it really did. Ultimately, I am me. I could give you any label under the sun, but that would only ever scratch the surface.
	In closing, my exotic name in conjunction with the realization of my lack of Spanish led to me to not know my internal self, and this loss of internal self jeopardized my social self. As I grew older and looked laterally though I noticed that labels are purely superficial, which put less of a burden on my own identity. Sometimes I wish I could tell my younger self and that I could change the way I had grown up - but then I would not be who I am today. This version of me could only exist by going through what I did and growing up the way I did. Changing things would mean changing me, and there is no guarantee it would be for the better.

Why does an intelligent woman have to be an unattractive woman? Why does an unintelligent woman have to be an attractive woman? Society has told women that men prefer a pretty girl to a smart girl. We have become so superficial as to judge someone on their appearance rather than their qualities. Women spend thousands to look and feel beautiful from cosmetics and plastic surgery. Now more than ever, our social media is full of half-naked skinny women glowing with a fresh tan and smiling with perfect white teeth. Do we ever ask ourselves; I wonder what her story is or what her aspirations in life are? No, the women who see that image will go to the gym or starve themselves, get a spray tan, and whiten their teeth. The men will awe the beautiful woman and think about how perfect she is. Over the years, women have faced yet another oppressing technique masked in competition with one another to be desirable; the beauty myth. Women have become so infatuated with how they look the matter of education, genuine connection, and identity are disregarded. Men have given themselves the power to mentally abuse women and persuade them into believing if they sit still and look pretty, they will be feminine and desired. Women with the intelligence and bravery to stand up for their rights disrupt males' institutional power, thus being cast as undesired and masculine. 
A bit of background for relevance; I am a tall, white, skinny, blonde woman. I am also majoring in biomedical engineering, which includes courses filled with mostly men and a few women. Growing up, my parents prioritized my education and taught me about my image's importance. How to carry yourself, which clothes to wear, how to interact with others, and everything a young woman learns. However, they never taught me that men would solely view me as a tall skinny unintelligent blonde. How that young men assume I was in the wrong class because this was Calculus 3, and what business would I have there? How older men would look at me and say, "You should smile more. It makes you look prettier." My life consists of men telling me how I should look, and if I do look that way, I should be content with life. 
One instance that still resonates with me is an interaction with one of my high school teachers. He asked, "What do you want to be when you grow up?" The most mundane and run-of-the-mill question people even ask it to kindergarteners. I responded with doctor or lawyer because I knew I wanted to have an A-list career. His response was genuinely demoralizing, saying I should lower my standards, maybe be a teacher or a nurse, something that would suit me better. He didn't know I was taking sophomore-level classes in 8th grade; he didn't know I had been on the Honor Roll since kindergarten; and he didn't know I was on the mathlete team. He only saw a pretty face that needed to mold into a category that fits the standard. 
As a young woman, I fully developed by age 15, which meant my parents needed to warn me of how to dress and carry myself yet again. Always dress to impress, but you must leave things up to the imagination. They failed to mention if you show no skin, you're a prude, but if you show too much skin, you're asking for it. So how do I, as a woman, find my true identity amongst the roadblocks, devaluation of my knowledge, and sexualization of my body? 
Naomi Wolf wrote a piece exposing the beauty myth and evaluating its effect on women. The beauty myth stems from the sexual liberation of women during the industrial revolution after women abandoned the feminine mystique of domesticity. At that point, the only feminine ideology left was beauty, thus creating this intangible idea of impossible standards for women to achieve. This standard, created by men's institutionalized power, pulls women's focus away from political issues such as equality and turns it towards beauty. Women now constantly compare themselves to skinnier, younger, and more developed women. Therefore, according to Wolf, eating disorders have grown exponentially, and cosmetic surgery is the fastest-growing medical specialty. Women will do whatever they can to be the most beautiful, desired, and fit the beauty standard. Have you ever wondered why older women get Botox and plastic surgery to look younger? When someone ages, male or female, they grow wiser, meaning age indicates intelligence. However, women must not be intelligent because they would threaten men's power, making them unattractive to men.
Men further instill this myth by not dating a girl more intelligent than them because if women were free from this hold, their power would contest men's power considerably. In her paper, Wolf mentions a caricature from 1960 of an "Ugly Feminist" which shows a masculine woman smoking a cigar. Society is making women believe that if they portray themselves as unintelligent, conceal their feelings, and don't cause any disturbance in male dominance; they are considered beautiful and feminine. On the other hand, if you are portraying intelligence and awareness of the oppression of women, you threaten male dominance; therefore, you are considered ugly and masculine. We must ask the question, why do women allow this to happen to them? The answer is more complex than just ignoring it because women are now permanently psychologically affected by the beauty myth. The only way for women to break free from the myth is to see the world through a different lens. Something challenging to achieve when our economy relies on the income from cosmetic companies resulting in the standardized beautiful woman plastered on every magazine, television, and billboard. 
If I were to look back on my personal experiences, I could understand why people view an unattractive woman as intelligent and why people view an attractive woman as unintelligent. Brilliant women stand to disrupt the male institutions and challenge their dominance. In turn, men accuse them of being ugly because men fear the power of a woman free from the shackles of the beauty myth. If women gain complete confidence and trust their knowledge, it will carry them much further than the makeup on their faces and the Botox in their cheeks. 
My fellow male classmates don't think I am capable because I am intelligent and beautiful, which they are intimidated by. My high school teacher attempted to discourage me because he was worried a witty woman would achieve more remarkable accomplishments than him, thus hindering his dominance. The problem is not the woman but the insecure men attempting to oppress women to feel better about themselves. My identity is not how many men like how I look but the intelligence and connections I possess. 
Sense of humor is another excellent example of the beauty myth. Men's sense of humor, when determining if they find a woman funny or not, is based on whether or not the woman laughs at his joke. On the other hand, women would choose a good sense of humor if the male told a good joke. In elementary school, the teacher would ask, "Are there any strong boys here that can help me carry this?" Notice how the teacher never asked if any strong girls could help because women should sit still and look pretty. In our society, instances of the beauty myth range in all age groups. 
Women need to see that men don't say derogatory things to them because they are true but because they are worried women will become as powerful as them, if not more powerful. Women can be conventionally beautiful and just as intelligent as someone who isn't conventionally beautiful. The same goes for a woman who isn't considered a classic beauty and can be just as unintelligent as a woman who is a classic beauty. Standardized beauty is another way for men to approve or disapprove of a woman's behavior and intelligence. Women are not less because they are women but because female beauty is used as a political weapon to oppress them.

In Peggy McIntosh’s article titled White Privilege she explains that she noticed how men often are unaware or don’t admit they are more privileged than women. When she became aware of this, she often became aware of the privilege that white people have over people of color, and how white people are often unaware of this privilege as well. In Mead’s The Self the I and the Me he explains his theory of self and how it relates to a person’s learned behaviors and their conception of self. 
Peggy explains that she believes white people are carefully taught not to a acknowledge their privilege. This makes them unaware that they even have it, and only by become aware of it can they do something to change it. The Boy’s Club
Growing up and to this day, I might frequently be considered a “tomboy.” A tomboy is a girl who exhibits characteristics associated with masculinity and prefers hanging out with the guys and ditching the “girly girls.” Why is there a special category for girls who enjoy wearing pants and playing in the mud versus masquerading in pretty dresses as princesses? Society creates neat categories for humans to fit into, and gender is a significant category. However, human beings “do” their gender in unique ways. So, a person might feel confused or upset if they see an individual who doesn’t automatically fit into their schema for the typical man or woman. Tomboys act outside the bounds of what a typical girl is expected to do. Such behavior tends to be more accepted than identifying as non-binary or transgender; nevertheless, it receives pushback.
My neighborhood was full of kids back in elementary school, and we would all hang out together after school and on the weekends. There were more guys than girls, and I was inclined to want to do whatever the boys were doing. I was good friends with the girls, too, but making up dances and playing with barbies did not sound all that appealing to me. I wanted to have nerf gun wars and lightsaber fights and play video games. I don’t know if it was ever an official name that we called ourselves, but the boys and I would always hang out in this storage room at my house called The Boy’s Club. I felt cool because I was the only girl allowed in there (even though it was my house).
Don’t get me wrong; there were times when I played dress-up and had the stereotypical sleepovers with my girl friends. I never felt like I would rather be a boy, but it felt more comfortable and more like me to hang with the guys. I would wear my hair up in a ponytail, burp like a beer-drunk man, and sit with my legs open (an unladylike position). My mom was not fond of this. I can’t tell you how often she told me to stop doing these things because girls don’t behave like that.
Candace West and Don Zimmerman examine gender from the lens of a performance or as something human beings are always doing in the context of social interactions. They clearly define the terms sex, sex category, and gender. First, sex is “a determination made through the application of socially agreed upon biological criteria for classifying persons as females” (i.e., genitals at birth or chromosomes; West and Zimmerman 127). Sex may seem as though it is concrete, but there is a myriad of chromosomal typings and physical displays of these typings that can make even sex ambiguous. Second, sex category is “achieved through application of the sex criteria, but in everyday life, categorization is established and sustained by the socially required identificatory displays that proclaim one’s membership” as males or females (West and Zimmerman 127). Identifiers such as hair length or body language help others categorize someone as one sex or the other because the sex of a person, or biological characteristics, is not typically readily available for everyone to perceive. One can be categorized as male and be seen as masculine even if a person lacks male sex criteria if their performance of gender is adequate. Gender is “the activity of managing situated conduct in light of normative conceptions of attitudes and activities appropriate for one’s sex category” (West and Zimmerman 127). Notice that gender is described as an activity that one does and is meant to signify and validate a person’s sex category. These three terms are complex and interconnected and must be analyzed together to understand how someone moves through the world as a gendered being.
Through visual clues, one might determine that my sex category is female. This determination is made by my stature, body language, voice, etc. I do not readily display my sex characteristics, but these clues help others visually identify me as a female. However, the way I “do” gender is ambiguous and depends on the context. West and Zimmerman state that displays of gender are context-dependent. I may perform a more feminine gender or a more masculine gender identity in different social interactions.
Returning to the neighborhood kids, I performed my gender differently when I was with the Boy’s Club than with the girls. The kids may have perceived my sex category to be female and, thus, I was treated as such, but the way I did my gender depended on the people. I was still feminine when I was with the boys, but I leaned into my more masculine traits when playing with them. Whereas with the girls, I remained more feminine. I roughhoused with the boys and was generally more assertive in this group. I was calm and passive with the girls. The boys accepted me into their group, but I was still a girl, so I couldn’t be hit or teased as much as the guys.
        	According to West and Zimmerman, our environment also impacts how we perform gender. We do gender by gathering resources from our surroundings. For example, I may have been doing gender in a more masculine way on the playground with the boys, but if I had to use the bathroom, I would choose between the girl’s and boy’s bathrooms. Due to my sex characteristics and the sex category others perceive me as, I use the bathroom designated by the stick figure with the triangle dress. However, as evident by gender-neutral bathrooms, bathrooms do not need to be separated based on sex characteristics. “Gendered” environments such as separate bathrooms reinforce the gender binary, strengthening our socialized schemas. I would be chastised if someone perceived my sex category as a woman and saw me go into the men’s bathroom. 
        	Even before birth, humans are placed into a category. An expecting mother might show an ultrasound picture of her baby boy to her friend, who might say, “wow, he looks like he’s going to grow up to be a big, strong man.” Conversely, if shown an ultrasound picture of a baby girl, the friend might say, “awh, look how cute she is. She’s going to be a heartbreaker.” As far as we know, fetuses are not socialized to perform gender to match their sex category while they’re in the womb; however, around preschool age is when children are taking on their socialized gender identity behaviors. West and Zimmerman discuss how little boys focus on how they affect the world physically and socially via physical strength. Little boys want to interact with the world and get their desired outcomes. In contrast, little girls focus on how they interact with the world via their appearance. They want to fit in by looking how they think little girls should look. This observation matches how I behaved in elementary school with the boys versus the girls. I roughhoused with boys to get what I wanted, and I played dress-up with the girls. I was still socialized as a girl, but, like most children, I didn’t completely follow the rules (no matter how much it annoyed my mom).
        	Tomboys are just a tiny exception to the gender binary in Western society. This term is used to designate a girl/woman who acts like a boy/man. Of course, human beings do their gender in various nuanced ways. Some are not born with the sex characteristics that match their gender identity and may identify as transgender. Some may not identify with any gender and describe themselves as non-binary or gender non-conforming. There are many examples of how humans convey their identity in their social interactions, and we must consider this when thinking about how we place people in categories. I’ve received a lot of judgment for being a tomboy, and others who do not strictly adhere to gender roles do too. When we think about gender as a performance and not as something that belongs to us, it takes away the idea that we have to be the thing that people perceive us to be. It is easier said than done to persuade people not to perceive our sex category. However, society can move toward accepting with open minds rather than judging.

Gender stereotypes have messed with the hiring scene for women because men are depicted as being better at most things than women, so they are the target interviewees. Sexual Harassment in the Workplace
In a workplace, women are known to have to put up with more concerning issues than a man. These issues can come in the form of sexual harassment and discrimination. The Matrix of Domination During Modern Day
The sociological paradigm known as the Matrix of Domination is where many are forced to deal with oppression due to their race, social class, gender, sexual identity, age, and religion. The more you meet, the more you are caught up in the matrix. One could describe the matrix as a spider web if they liked.

(1)Woman + (2)Person of Color + (3)Transgender + (4)18 to 25 years old = Deep Within The Matrix

 According to Collins, “The Matrix of Domination stems from Eurocentric, masculinist thought which are institutions, paradigms, and any elements of the knowledge-validation procedure controlled by white males and whose purpose is to represent a white male standpoint.”
 Before diving deeper into the Matrix of Domination, it is important to discuss Collins’ explanation of the role of black feminist thought. Afrocentric feminist thought rejects additive approaches to oppression by utilizing knowledge to resist domination and empower those dealing with oppression (Collins, 1990). This not only helps shift the way we think about oppression but also allows us to better assess the “truth” behind many current debates (Collins, 1990). Collins expresses that black feminist thought views the system of oppression as being part of the intense structure of domination. She also states that domination operates by seducing, pressuring, or forcing African American women and other members of subordinated groups to replace individual and cultural ways of knowing with the dominant group’s specialized thought. The author relays that dominant groups aim to do this because they realize that gaining control over this dimension of subordinate group’s lives, simplifies control. This paper will examine how the Matrix of Domination affects minorities by specifically discussing Black Transgender Women, Transgender people of color, and Latina warehouse workers. The more minorities you are a part of, the more predisposed you are to oppression. 
Now, onto one of the topics at hand; the Matrix of Domination and Black Transgender Women. Black Transgender Women are probably the best “agents of knowledge” because they receive the least privilege, meaning that they have dealt with all aspects of the matrix for the longest time. During the Summer of 2020, six black transgender women under the age of thirty-two were killed over a period of nine days. As stated by Foreisteire, “...hate crimes against transgender and gender non-conforming individuals have been on the rise for years, with the number of murders in 2020 already almost surpassing that of 2019. Of the 26 victims so far this year and the 27 victims last year, the majority have been Black transgender women under the age of 30.” The reasons that Black Transgender women are killed at such crazy rates is due to the mix of homophobia, transphobia, sexism, homophobia, etc. which are ideas that stem from Eurocentric, masculinist thought (Foreisteire, 2020). 
Navigating Community Institutions: Black Transgender Women's Experiences in Schools, the Criminal Justice System, and Churches, written by Louis F. Graham, further displays the oppression that Black Transgender Women face. This study aims to bring attention to the issue by collecting the life histories of ten black transgender women between eighteen and twenty-four years old, all living in Detroit, Michigan (Graham, 2014). It explores the institutional violence, harassment, and discrimination they face, specifically at schools, churches, and within the criminal justice system (Graham, 2020). 
Some statistics that shed the light on the negativity this specific group of people face are explained within this article. For example, Graham quotes that, “In 2001, the Gay, Lesbian, and Straight Education Network (GLESN) conducted a School Climate Survey and found that 82 % of LGBT students reported being the victim of sexual, physical, or verbal harassment; over 90 % indicated that they regularly heard anti-LGBT comments at school; and nearly 25 % heard these comments from school personnel (Bauer, 2002).” Also, the bullying that occurs in school towards transgender people is so intense that it leads many to develop numerous mood disorders and suicidal ideations. The mood disorders one can develop from the environment Black Transgender Women endure can range from Major Depressive Disorder to Anxiety Disorder to Panic Disorder and more.
When one feels like this or is getting bullied, they are often told by a counselor or friend to turn to their community for support but when it comes to Transgender people of color, even that may not be an option. The majority of the time, Transgender people of color are not accepted by their own cultures because how they identify goes against their cultures’ set of beliefs. In turn, they feel alone and isolated. 
Another big issue Transgender people of color have to deal with is fetishization. Transgender people of color’s experiences of sexual objectification: Locating sexual objectification within a matrix of domination, written by Flores, Watson, Allen, Ford, Serpe, Choo, and Ferrel, interviewed fifteen Transgender people of color about their experiences with sexual objectification (Flores, Watson, Allen, Ford, Serpe, Choo, & Ferrel, 2018). The authors state that, “results suggested participants’ sexual objectification experiences were shaped by the intersections of cissexism, sexism, and racism, and that participants experienced various levels of privilege and oppression based on their specific identities,” which once again, ties in with the Eurocentric, masculinist thought (Flores, Watson, Allen, Ford, Serpe, Choo, & Ferrel, 2018).  It is well known that Transgender people of color face more unequal treatment, assault (whether it be physical or sexual, and harassment than any other group whether it be White Transgender people, Lesbian or Gay people, etc. These findings also show that “TPOC, especially TPOC women may be at-risk for oppression-based victimization (Flores, Watson, Allen, Ford, Serpe, Choo, & Ferrel, 2018).”
As a result, when one takes a look at the everyday lives of Transgender people of color or specifically, Black Transgender Women, they see exactly how dominated these people are. Due to ideas created hundreds of years ago of what is socially “correct” or what “should be”, these people are predisposed to overall, poor quality of life just because of others’ opinions and actions. 
Another example is Desperate Fortunes: Latina Warehouse Workers in the "Matrix of Domination", written by Danielle J. Lindemann and Teresa M. Boyer, applies Collins theory to data from focus groups with immigrant Latina “perma-temp” warehouse workers.  A “perma-temp” is a temporary employee who works for an extended period for a single staffing client. One main topic of this article and the one above is Intersectionality Theory. Basically, “Women of color who were involved with these movements understood that race, class, gender, and sexuality could not be explored and addressed separately; rather these categories are part and parcel of interlocking systems of oppression (Lindemann & Boyer, 2019)”. The study states that if one, “...apply(ies) insights from intersectionality theory to the topic of migrant organizing, and contends that class, race, and gender are collectively key to understanding the labor market experiences of immigrant women.” This is basically the “matrix” that leaves those controlled. 
Another issue that these factory women have to deal with is harassment within the work environment. This article tells of one story where the managers and supervisors see these women as objects and sexual beings and how they were only hired if they met the supervisors’ “level of desirability”. Not only did they have to deal with that, but they had to deal with pay inequality as well.  
If one looks over all of the information provided, one can draw the conclusion that the further into the matrix one falls, the more they seem “predisposed” to oppression. If you are a woman, you may have to deal with not being paid the same amount as a man for the same job when you have the same qualification. If you are a woman of color, you are even more likely to not be chosen for a job compared to a white man, a man of color, or a white woman. The pattern becomes worse and worse the farther you fall into the matrix. It seems that if one is not a straight, white male, the fewer opportunities you will be given and the higher the chances of you being bullied, assaulted, harassed, treated unfairly, etc. 
This leads to my last important point. America prides itself, saying that it is a country of “equal opportunity for all of its citizens” but, how can that statement be true if you are born as or identify as any one of the categories that isn’t a straight, white male? The answer is simple: It’s false. You can not control what you are or how you feel and it is unfair that one may have to deal with extreme forces of oppression because of things out of their control. 
In conclusion, the more minorities you are a part of, the more predisposed you are to oppression. Black Transgender Women are the best “agents of knowledge” because of how far they are in the matrix and because of all the dangers they experience and face. Latina factory workers are forced to deal with terrible work environments and are harassed simply because of who they are. This is all one sad, modern-day, multi-century truth.
 Take a look at the news and read the titles: the Black Lives Matter movement; the Black Trans Lives Matter movement; the Stop Asian Hate movement; the Stop Immigrant Hate movement; the LGBT movement; the Gender Equality movement. Speak up and be a part of the change. Don’t let what is unacceptable, continue. Don’t be an oppressor and don’t allow yourself to be oppressed.

White Privilege
My brothers are two of six African American students in their entire private high school. I was a pre-professional ballet student for four years away from home, and yet I was one of two African American students my entire time there. What is the reason for this? Is it really that only predominantly white people can afford a private high school? No, it’s much more than that. 
The systemic issues in our society continue to benefit and support white people automatically, while oppressing people of color, which is known as “white privilege”. Many people have denied this term stating that: their life hasn’t been easy, that they’ve had to work hard, or that they are poor. That’s not what it means. White privilege is like an “invisible package of unearned assets'' (McIntosh, pg. 30) that white people receive just because of their skin color. White privilege is not something that can be taught or learned, it is automatically given to any white individual. It does not matter the age or gender, you still have white privilege. 
So why do so many people resist to acknowledge it? Well it comes down to fear and refusing to see it. The fact that many people with privilege don’t try to see how they fall into that category, because it simply doesn’t impact them. Then, there are people who know that the system exists but they don’t want to change it because that same system gives them benefits. Instead, white privilege is used by the dominant group as a way to further racialize African Americans. 
Whether it pertains to housing, lending, education, medical disparities, interaction with law enforcement or simply just everyday bias - African Americans disproportionately end up being negatively impacted in all of these categories. As a result, you see more people of color: receiving inadequate education (and therefore often leading to inadequate employment later on), incarcerated, suffering in poverty, labeled as criminals or “thugs”, and more. This provides the exact ammunition for those holding the power to attribute those things to being African American, rather than due to institutionalized racism and white privilege. 
Racism is an ongoing issue that has yet to be resolved but there are not enough people doing anything about it. You can learn about the different cultures instead of judging and making comments about it, and accept and respect people's differences and beliefs.  Schools should teach about it more, people should discuss it with others, get to know someone before making assumptions about them; these are all good places to start. Instead, for example, most schools provide a whitewashed education; rather than teaching students in Wilmington about the 1898 Wilmington massacre, we learn all about what white people did, and how Columbus was a hero. 
When people are trying so hard to not be racist they might try to make some jokes or claim that they don’t see color to come across as an inclusive person. However when someone says, “I don’t see color” it is the same thing as saying I don’t see our differences and that's not necessarily good. Everyone doesn’t believe the same things or think the same way, so yes there are differences and it’s how you react to those differences that determines if you are racist or not. There are some people who try to avoid the topic of racism altogether because they believe that if we don’t talk about it then it won’t be an issue any longer, but as a society we are not at that point yet. Instead of avoiding the topic we have to learn how to embrace and accept the differences that make each of us who we are. A big part of this is the school systems fail to educate students properly. School systems need to incorporate a more diverse system for learning considering most people get their education from school, if it is not being learned in school people are most likely to grow up unaware of how important racism is in society and are less likely to learn about it as they get older which is a problem. 
Racism is not something that should be ignored or silenced. There are plenty of people who try to silence the ones fighting for equality, and unfortunately the system and power of white privilege allows that to happen; this is one of the reasons there hasn’t been enough impactful change to systemic racism. Those people who are trying to silence the others are often wearing the privilege of being white, and are often the same people who don’t believe that racism is still a problem. Frequently these are the same people that claim they “don’t see color.” This is a common theme I have encountered throughout my experience. A majority of those people are also white, and because they are white they have never had to experience the oppression that people of color have to deal with every single day. Instead, they have the benefit of white privilege. White people automatically have one less obstacle to overcome in daily life. It doesn’t mean life is easy and simple for white people, but it does mean that there is not the added layer of skin color to make things more difficult. 
So how does white privilege really make things easier for white people? As a result of racializing and stereotyping, it is often easier for them to find and keep jobs no matter their previous experience. They do not have the hurdle of being stereotyped at the outset just due to their skin color, and this provides an advantage. Some interviewers won’t even allow a black person to come in for an interview or will offer them a lower position that they could work, even if their resume shows they have a lot of experience and are better for the job (Pager Discrimination article). This is an example of the interviewer being racist because they don’t want to hire someone who is black. Or you can look at what happens in the education system. As a result of racializing, it is more likely that a brown or black skinned student will be overlooked, labeled, or worse. One bad incident early on can start a cycle which makes it harder for these students to receive the same education or experience the same opportunities. 
My family has to make conscious decisions of where we are going and what the risks may be. Driving through certain geographic areas at night may not be smart, so we try to avoid that. We have learned from a young age what to do when a police officer pulls us over, or interacts with us, to be sure that we don’t do or say anything that could be used against us. None of my friends have had to go through that same “talk”. This is not something that we should have to teach young children, telling them to be careful how you act around certain people, and having to constantly be in fear of their life.
I’m a proud black person. I’m a proud white person. Two very similar sentences with very different meanings. Saying that you are a proud black person is saying: I am proud to be me despite society being largely against who I am. It is the idea that you had to fight for equality in this country and that it was never something that you just had. It is empowering. It’s saying I am proud that I have overcome the oppression, racism, hardships, and constant negativity that you receive just for having brown or black skin. It shows that even after being criticized by the beauty standards and by white supremacists, I still love me for me and wouldn’t want to change. However, saying “I am proud to be white”, is not the same. As discussed above, merely by being white, there are automatically certain things that you can do that a black person can’t do. There was nothing that you had to risk your life over or spend decades upon decade trying fighting for something, like equality. From the start everything is automatically easier. With that being said there is a difference between being confident with how you look or your ethnicity and saying you are proud of what your culture has done in the past. 
White privilege is an insidious creature, living in us and among us, continuing to foster a destructive system - rather than change it. With education, awareness, willingness to be anti-racist, and advocacy, it is possible to shift this dynamic; we can shift the dynamic so that white peivikege is instead used to make impactful changes to a racist system. This would then ultimately eliminate white privilege. While there is still a percentage of the population who would not want that, we should hope that there is enough power in the percentage of people who do. If awareness of the issue is raised, and changes are made in how people of color are racialized - there is hope to change the longstanding institutionalized racism that this country was built on.

In our society, it is evident that certain groups are put into stereotypical categories and are therefore treated differently. A prime example of this is how women purposely fall into certain roles of femininity in order to pertain to what is considered normal in society. While women have come a long way in terms of obtaining rights and being able attain similar opportunities as men, many still fall into the trap of still trying to pertain to the male gaze. So the question remains, if we are truly equals, then why do women feel the need to portray themselves in a way that is deemed acceptable by society? 
It is safe to say that times are very different today than they used to be. A little under a century ago, women were fighting just for the right to vote in America and to not be treated as property of men. Nowadays, women are scientists, doctors, filmmakers, and have opportunities to pursue basically any field of interest that they wish. Although things have never been better for women, our society is constantly being inundated with subliminal messages regarding femininity. In stores we see handbags in glittery pink that say “You go girl!”. On TV there are commercials for barbie dolls with tagline that read, “you can be whatever you want!”. Everywhere you look, there are false messages about female empowerment, with subtext that essentially tells women that they can do what they want, but they need to remain feminine to do so. This therefore make women feel uncomfortable int their own skin, and that they are not allowed to wear what they want.  I have also seen examples in college as well. The parties are all on the men’s terms and are about them being able to meet girls. After observing the rugby team’s habits, he noticed that many of the players engaged in defensive othering as well as other toxic habits. The girls portrayed a strong sense of femininity both on and off the field, to combat possible notions that they were not girly enough, due to the tough nature of the sport. There are many stereotypes surrounding tough female athletes and the rugby girls did everything they could to not fall into them. This created a hard scenario for the girls, because not only did they have to prove themselves on the field, but they had to remain feminine and “pretty” while doing it. This feeds into the subordination that women constantly face and sets a standard for other women to follow suit, or risk being othered.

Not only did the girls feel a strong need to fit certain standards, but they also put down other women and shamed them if they felt they didn’t belong. This is very dangerous. The actions of the majority of a group have a strong influence on its members because it is simply human nature to want to fit in and do what others are doing. This idea of being feminine, dressing up, needing to speak a certain way, are all things that have fallen into the collective consciousness of women in general.

While there is a great deal of empowerment going on, there is also a struggle for women to stay in certain positions unless they act a certain way. Even after that, women feel the need to control themselves so they fit into a category that is palatable and accepted. It is hard to say how this issue could eventually be resolved, but it seems that one of the main things that has to happen is that women need to work together more to fight this silent sexism. I feel that only after this, will women be able to take down these stereotypes that have followed us over centuries, and be able to rise above them. Racism and Religion – How it all Fits. Or does it?

Harari has many adamant and powerful positions which discusses in his book: 21 Lessons for the 21st Century.  With his impassioned arguments, he shares similar views with other authors, economists, and philosophers, as well as shares quite contrary views with some people. This essay will highlight just a few of those similarities or differences, between Harari and other writers and thinkers.
One example of this is on the subject of racism, specifically, how it has evolved and changed over time – to modern day. Michael Omi and Howard Winant, in the  excerpt “Racial Formations”, from the book Racial Formations in the United States: From the 1960s to the 1980s, assert that as race is a social construct, it was developed and evolved from just having differences in people’s skin color. In fact, the authors in this article argue that the use of racism in this new, modernized, evolved way, is very much deliberate and a way to oppress groups of people. The way this is done is by attributing specific negative characteristics or behaviors, to certain groups of people – based on skin color, or country of origin, for example. As Omi and Wyant write: “Skin color ‘differences’ are thought to explain perceived differences in intellectual, physical, and artistic temperaments, and to justify distinct treatment of racially identified individuals and groups” (Omi & Winant, page 23). Race became a way to explain societal issues and failures, blaming issues on negative and racist stereotypes of African Americans. The authors here argue that this shift in ‘racializing’ groups of people is a more modern day development. This attributing of negative traits to people of color is something that the authors assert has further perpetuated a system which is full of systemic racism, which is also then absorbed by our society. People then tend to accept and believe what they are hearing and seeing on various forms of media, as to how some groups of people may act. This is a way for human beings to explain problems, to disassociate themselves from ‘bad people’ or ‘bad things’ and to further oppress groups of people.
Similarly, Harari believes that racism is alive and unfortunately, well; however, he argues that the way it presents has evolved from being based upon biological differences, to focusing on an individual’s culture. Even with this evolution, racism is still very much about judging an individual or group of people based on assumptions, stereotypes, and bias.  This is similar to Omi and Winant’s beliefs.
In his book, Harari dives into the issues and beliefs surrounding immigration. Immigration of a “foreign” person who does not come from there, into a new country. Using the context of immigration, Harari points out how racism has evolved into something different today.  This evolution of racism began with the time period where it was both publicly, and widely accepted, that white people were the superior race. Of course through history and all of the events that took place, Harari points out, there was a shift in this “Racism was seen not only as morally abysmal but also as scientifically bankrupt” ( Harari, p 149). However, in its place came a new type of racism, or a new demonstration of it.  While the morality factor, as well as scientific evidence, discourages people from stating that a person of color is inferior because they are ‘biologically’ different, there is now the belief that based on where a person is from (location-wise, or national origin), there are negative stereotypes and assumptions that can be attributed to that group of people. This is racism, just in a different disguise, according to Harari. As he writes: “Saying that black people tend to commit crimes because they have substandard genes is out; saying that they tend to commit crimes because they come from dysfunctional subcultures is very much in” (Harari, page 152). 
Harari’s stance on this evolved form of racism is very much aligned with Omi and Winant’s position. Harari does take it a step further than Omi and Winant, where he points out that this ‘new’ form of racism may look on the surface like it is less racist than the former. However, as Harari discusses, in the context of immigration – if the pressure is to get the immigrants to become more like ‘us’, then it really is no better: “…present day culturists might be more tolerant than traditional racists – if only the ‘others’ adopt our culture, we will accept them as our equals. On the other hand, that could result in far stronger pressures on the ‘others’ to assimilate, and in far harsher criticism of their failure to do so” (Harari, page 153). This perfectly illustrates the issue with viewing this new racism as a better or more tolerant form. It still remains the same: judging individuals based on assumptions and stereotypes, and using negative attributes to label an entire group of people – merely based on where they are from, what their ethnic background is.
On another topic, religion, Harari differs in his view from Max Weber. While the issue of religion and its involvement in our policy making or social interactions is separate and different from religion, there is of course some overlap.
Max Weber, in his article titled “The Spirit of Capitalism and the Iron Cage”, writes that religion is something that not only ‘can’ create social change, but that it has historically been used, and can still be used, and should be used. In fact, Weber argues that the Puritan people were “called” (Weber, p 105) to their particular work, whereas today, people are instead “forced.”  Weber further argues that the religious calling, spirit and reasoning behind one’s work, historically, is what made it something meaningful, significant, and powerful. In contrast, today’s modern day Capitalism, Weber argues, is devoid of that religious foundation. Without it, Weber asserts that this creates a lack of values, no sort of satisfaction from work, and really a lack of anything good. In this way, Weber asserts that this has led humans to simply be motivated by the making of money, rather than working for some higher purpose, to benefit society or other human beings. Interestingly, Weber believes that religion is actually where capitalism first originated from. However, modern day capitalism, in his view, has strayed from where it began. Rather than being “called” to a particular work, and doing so as a result – currently, we are now just doing the work, to make the money. This, Weber believes, moves away from the religious foundation, which is to our detriment as a society.
	Harari’s position on the interplay of Religion and policy making and politics is vastly different from Weber’s. Contrary to Weber’s stance, Harari asserts the belief that there really is no appropriate place for religion in the making of policy, or social change, in our society.  Harari argues that the involvement of religion is dangerous, in large part due to the fact that there are so many different religions. Whose is right? Whose is better, or best? Every religion thinks their religion is the “right” one. So, Harari argues, how does that possibly fit into policy making and politics. While his views do not necessarily directly contradict with Weber’s belief that religion can motivate a person to operate in a spiritually-led way, his views differ overall -in that he believes religion does not have an appropriate place in the political and  policy relations in our society and world. As Harari highlights about human nature and thinking: “National, religious and cultural tensions are made worse by the grandiose feeling that my nation, my religion, and my culture are the most important in the world -and therefore my interests should come before the interests of anyone else, or of humankind as a whole” (Harari, page 183). This sums up his concern pretty perfectly, pointing out that while each religion believes itself to be the best, the most correct, then this would lead to disagreement in actions, policy, and beliefs – due to the simple fact that there are multiple different religions. 
	Within his argument, Harari focuses a lot on the concept of humility. This concept is something he says is lacking in the use of religion within politics and policy making in our world.  There is no humility when each religion believes their own to be true, to be the best, to be superior to others, and the “right” one.  This perfectly illustrates the issue involving religion on the biggest stage – world human relations and policy making. In contrast, Weber is arguing that Christianity in particular, has been, and should be, the moral compass to determine how to motivate individuals and groups, and within the making of policies and effecting social changes. 
	As you can see, even where Harari may align his views with other notable thinkers and writers, there is considerable difference between him and others. Harari’s book helps to set forth his positions in totality, and presents the arguments with sufficient substance and reasoning. The two topics of religion and racism are two topics which have received considerable attention, thinking and writing from various individuals over time – and this continues to be the case today. As a result, we can see that Harari has some similar views – for example – with Omi and Winant; whereas, he differs significantly in views on religion (in some aspects at least) from those views of Max Weber. Religion and race/racism are topics which are complex and extremely laden with human emotions, and deep conviction.
